Initial commit from Create Next App

Specify default Node.js version for nvm

v22 is the current LTS version of Node.js

Extend TSConfig from recommended base

I removed any compiler options from tsconfig.json that duplicated those
in the base configuration.

Sort dependencies in package.json

This is to ensure a clean diff when the next dependency is added.
Add VS Code launch configurations to facilitate debugging

Add website icons

icon16.svg is the source file for the 16px icon; all other sizes are
generated from icon.svg. All PNGs were losslessly compressed using
Trimage [1].

[1] https://trimage.org/

Add fonts

I've used `font-display: optional` because I want to avoid delaying the
rendering of the page while the fonts are downloaded, and also avoid the
flash of unstyled text or layout shift that can occur if the fonts are
swapped after the initial render.

Add Sass module for breakpoints

Up to now I've been able to use vanilla CSS and custom CSS properties
to define common colours and dimensions.

However CSS custom properties cannot be used in media queries, so to
avoid having to hardcode the breakpoints wherever they appear, I've
decided to take a development dependency on Sass and define them as Sass
variables.

At this point we only have one breakpoint but I more to be added in due
course.

Add internationalization

The bulk of the changes in this commit were made by simply following the
instructions in the next-intl 'App Router setup without I18n routing'
guide [1]. The only exception being the resolution of locale based on
the Accept-Language header which is not covered in the guide.

For that I used the same `Negotiator` and `@formatjs/intl-localematcher`
packages as the next-intl middleware uses for the same purpose [2].

I initially tried to use the `Negotiator.language()` function instead of
taking a the dependency on `@formatjs/intl-localematcher`. However, when
using `Negotiator.language()`, I hit upon some very counterintuitive
behaviour (such as "en-GB,fr-CH;q=0.7,en;q=0.3" resolving to "fr") that
is currently considered 'as intended' by the package maintainers [3] and
therefore ended up using `@formatjs/intl-localematcher` as well.

Note also that the next-intl middleware applies some reordering of
available locales [4] as a workaround for a separate `@formatjs` issue
[5]. I have not done the same here as the two available locales have the
same specificity.

[1] https://next-intl.dev/docs/getting-started/app-router/without-i18n-routing
[2] https://github.com/amannn/next-intl/blob/79c20855d523cb9d467bac08969244928596ced0/packages/next-intl/src/middleware/resolveLocale.tsx#L40
[3] https://github.com/jshttp/negotiator/issues/54#issuecomment-473358325
[4] https://github.com/amannn/next-intl/blob/79c20855d523cb9d467bac08969244928596ced0/packages/next-intl/src/middleware/resolveLocale.tsx#L28
[5] https://github.com/formatjs/formatjs/issues/4469

issue.title: Phase 3: AI Model Integration Hub
issue.body:
## Overview
Implement a comprehensive AI model integration hub that supports multiple providers and intelligent switching between models based on task requirements and availability.

## Technical Requirements

### Core Features
- **Multi-Provider Support**
  - OpenAI (GPT-4, GPT-3.5, DALL-E, Whisper)
  - Anthropic (Claude 3 Opus, Sonnet, Haiku)
  - Google (Gemini Pro, Bard, PaLM)
  - Local LLMs (Ollama, LlamaCPP, GPT4All)
  - Hugging Face models
  - Replicate API integration

- **Model Switching & Routing**
  - Intelligent model selection based on task type
  - Automatic fallback on rate limits or failures
  - Load balancing across providers
  - Context-aware model routing

- **Cost Optimization Engine**
  - Real-time cost tracking per request
  - Budget alerts and limits
  - Model cost comparison
  - Automatic switching to cheaper models when appropriate
  - Token usage optimization

- **Performance Benchmarking**
  - Response time tracking
  - Quality scoring system
  - A/B testing framework
  - Model comparison dashboard
  - Custom evaluation metrics

### Architecture Design
```typescript
interface ModelProvider {
  id: string;
  type: 'openai' | 'anthropic' | 'google' | 'local' | 'replicate';
  models: Model[];
  rateLimit: RateLimitConfig;
  pricing: PricingConfig;
  capabilities: ModelCapabilities[];
}

interface ModelRouter {
  selectModel(task: Task): Model;
  fallbackChain: Model[];
  costThreshold: number;
  performanceRequirements: PerformanceConfig;
}
```

### Implementation Details
1. **Provider Abstraction Layer**
   - Unified API interface
   - Standard request/response format
   - Error handling and retry logic
   - Connection pooling

2. **Cost Management**
   - Token counting for all providers
   - Real-time pricing updates
   - Budget allocation per team/project
   - Cost prediction before execution

3. **Performance Monitoring**
   - Latency tracking
   - Success/failure rates
   - Quality metrics
   - Provider uptime monitoring

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Support for at least 5 AI providers
- [ ] Automatic failover with <100ms overhead
- [ ] Cost tracking accuracy within 1% of actual bills
- [ ] Performance dashboard with real-time metrics
- [ ] API response time <50ms for model selection
- [ ] 99.9% uptime for routing service
- [ ] Complete unit test coverage (>90%)
- [ ] Integration tests for all providers
- [ ] Documentation for adding new providers

## Dependencies
- Redis for caching and rate limiting
- PostgreSQL for metrics storage
- Prometheus for monitoring
- Grafana for visualization

## Priority
**P0** - Critical for multi-model support

## Estimated Effort
3 weeks (2 developers)

## Technical Lead
@Elena_Volkov - Performance optimization critical for model switching

## Related Issues
- Links to authentication system
- Connects with billing system
- Requires monitoring infrastructure
